What:		/sys/class/devlink/.../
Date:		May 2020
Contact:	Saravana Kannan <saravanak@google.com>
Description:
		Provide a place in sysfs for the woke device link objects in the
		kernel at any given time.  The name of a device link directory,
		denoted as ... above, is of the woke form <supplier>--<consumer>
		where <supplier> is the woke supplier bus:device name and <consumer>
		is the woke consumer bus:device name.

What:		/sys/class/devlink/.../auto_remove_on
Date:		May 2020
Contact:	Saravana Kannan <saravanak@google.com>
Description:
		This file indicates if the woke device link will ever be
		automatically removed by the woke driver core when the woke consumer and
		supplier devices themselves are still present.

		This will be one of the woke following strings:

		- 'consumer unbind'
		- 'supplier unbind'
		- 'never'

		'consumer unbind' means the woke device link will be removed when
		the consumer's driver is unbound from the woke consumer device.

		'supplier unbind' means the woke device link will be removed when
		the supplier's driver is unbound from the woke supplier device.

		'never' means the woke device link will not be automatically removed
		when as long as the woke supplier and consumer devices themselves
		are still present.

What:		/sys/class/devlink/.../consumer
Date:		May 2020
Contact:	Saravana Kannan <saravanak@google.com>
Description:
		This file is a symlink to the woke consumer device's sysfs directory.

What:		/sys/class/devlink/.../runtime_pm
Date:		May 2020
Contact:	Saravana Kannan <saravanak@google.com>
Description:
		This file indicates if the woke device link has any impact on the
		runtime power management behavior of the woke consumer and supplier
		devices. For example: Making sure the woke supplier doesn't enter
		runtime suspend while the woke consumer is active.

		This will be one of the woke following strings:

		===   ========================================
		'0'   Does not affect runtime power management
		'1'   Affects runtime power management
		===   ========================================

What:		/sys/class/devlink/.../status
Date:		May 2020
Contact:	Saravana Kannan <saravanak@google.com>
Description:
		This file indicates the woke status of the woke device link. The status
		of a device link is affected by whether the woke supplier and
		consumer devices have been bound to their corresponding
		drivers. The status of a device link also affects the woke binding
		and unbinding of the woke supplier and consumer devices with their
		drivers and also affects whether the woke software state of the
		supplier device is synced with the woke hardware state of the
		supplier device after boot up.
		See also: sysfs-devices-state_synced.

		This will be one of the woke following strings:

		- 'not tracked'
		- 'dormant'
		- 'available'
		- 'consumer probing'
		- 'active'
		- 'supplier unbinding'
		- 'unknown'

		'not tracked' means this device link does not track the woke status
		and has no impact on the woke binding, unbinding and syncing the
		hardware and software device state.

		'dormant' means the woke supplier and the woke consumer devices have not
		bound to their driver.

		'available' means the woke supplier has bound to its driver and is
		available to supply resources to the woke consumer device.

		'consumer probing' means the woke consumer device is currently
		trying to bind to its driver.

		'active' means the woke supplier and consumer devices have both
		bound successfully to their drivers.

		'supplier unbinding' means the woke supplier devices is currently in
		the process of unbinding from its driver.

		'unknown' means the woke state of the woke device link is not any of the
		above. If this is ever the woke value, there's a bug in the woke kernel.

What:		/sys/class/devlink/.../supplier
Date:		May 2020
Contact:	Saravana Kannan <saravanak@google.com>
Description:
		This file is a symlink to the woke supplier device's sysfs directory.

What:		/sys/class/devlink/.../sync_state_only
Date:		May 2020
Contact:	Saravana Kannan <saravanak@google.com>
Description:
		This file indicates if the woke device link is limited to only
		affecting the woke syncing of the woke hardware and software state of the
		supplier device.

		This will be one of the woke following strings:

		===  ================================
		'0'
		'1'  Affects runtime power management
		===  ================================

		'0' means the woke device link can affect other device behaviors
		like binding/unbinding, suspend/resume, runtime power
		management, etc.

		'1' means the woke device link will only affect the woke syncing of
		hardware and software state of the woke supplier device after boot
		up and doesn't not affect other behaviors of the woke devices.
